attribute text: Species name Macrophyte species name At the beginning of the belowground macrophyte production study (1980-1982), roots and rhizomes were categorized into species.
label: species Name

attribute text: day sampling day In order to estimate net annual belowground macrophyte production, core samples of the belowground biomass were harvested in the late spring and in the fall. Shoot initiation early in the growing season depletes most of the belowground standing crop, and therefore spring sampling was done quickly (within 2 weeks) to capture this state. Underground biomass then reaches its seasonal maxima in the fall and was captured with the fall sampling.
label: biomass

attribute text: month sampling month In order to estimate net annual belowground macrophyte production, core samples of the belowground biomass were harvested in the late spring and in the fall. Underground biomass then reaches its seasonal maxima in the fall and was captured with the fall sampling.
label: biomass

attribute text: year sampling year Data for belowground macrophyte production (MBG) was collected form 1980-1989; however, this data table contains only the data from 1980. In order to estimate net annual belowground macrophyte production, core samples of the belowground biomass were harvested in the late spring and in the fall. Shoot initiation early in the growing season depletes most of the belowground standing crop, and therefore spring sampling was done quickly (within 2 weeks) to capture this state. Underground biomass then reaches its seasonal maxima in the fall and was captured with the fall sampling.
label: biomass

attribute text: day sampling day In order to estimate net annual belowground macrophyte production, core samples of the belowground biomass were harvested in the late spring and in the fall. Shoot initiation early in the growing season depletes most of the belowground standing crop, and therefore spring sampling was done quickly (within 2 weeks) to capture this state. Underground biomass then reaches its seasonal maxima in the fall and was captured with the fall sampling.

attribute text: spec_code species code All macroinvertebrates were sorted to the appropriate taxonomic level required to determine trophic level, and the total number of each taxon was recorded. Identification to family was adequate, however Chironomidae were further classified to the Tanypodinae subfamily (predator) and all other subfamilies as Non-Tanypodinae (herbivore).

total_biomass_mg total biomass of sample (mg) A representative sample of all invertebrate taxa and size classes from all sorted samples (with the exception of emergence trap samples) were kept to determine biomass. The representative individuals were from each taxa and sample type were rinsed with distilled water and then placed in weighed and dried (105ºC for 24 hrs.) aluminum pans. The invertebrates were then dried at 105 ºC overnight and the pans were weighed again the following day. When 500 individuals of the same taxon or size class had been collected and weighed, where the mean weight was < 1.0mg, and 200 individuals from any taxa had a mean weight > 1.0 mg, these groups no longer had to be dried for their dry-weight determination (Ross and Murkin, 1989).
h2o_depth water depth (cm) water depth recorded at litter bag site centimeter
label: water depth

attribute text: p_conc phosphorus concentration (mg/g) Note: to determine percent nutrient remaining e.g. percent nitrogen remaining = ((final_odw*n_conc)/(orig_odw*'control nitrogen concentration'))*100, where orig_odw is the corrected fresh weight to estimate initial oven dry weight, and 'control nitrogen concentration' is the average of the three nitrogen concentrations recorded from the control litter bags, for a particular species (i.e. for Scholochloa (020201), control nitrogen concentration = 1.01 (average of 0.72,1.26,1.06)) MilligramsPerGram

final_odw litter dry weight at collection (oven dry weight; g) samples were dried to a constant weight at 80 degrees C.

p_conc phosphorus concentration (mg/g) litter nutrient concentration; To reduce the number of samples analyzed for total carbon, nitrogen and phosphorus, ground samples were pooled by species, water depth and collection date prior to chemical analysis. When possible, five litter bag samples were combined to make 1 sample for nutrient analysis. Water depths were stratified into 30-cm intervals: i.e. 0 cm = unflooded, 1- 30 cm = shallow, 31-60 cm = medium,  60-90 cm = deep sites, and >90cm.

attribute text: titerStrength  A titer (or titre) is a way of expressing concentration. Titer testing employs serial dilution to obtain approximate quantitative information from an analytical procedure that inherently only evaluates as positive or negative. The titer corresponds to the highest dilution factor that still yields a positive reading. For example, positive readings in the first 8 serial twofold dilutions translate into a titer of 1:256 (i.e., 2−8). Titers are sometimes expressed by the denominator only, for example 1:256 is written 256.

attribute text: T T IButton Thermochron temperature loggers (Maxim Inc., Dallas, TX) were buried at each grid point to a depth of 10 cm and temperature was logged for three days in continuous 30 min intervals. Mean soil temperatures at 10 cm depths were obtained for the three days of measurements and normalized within a measurement period. Higher soil temperature estimated from this normalization indicated that soil temperature at a particular microsite was higher than the mean of the 50 grid points. These observations were used to describe spatial variability of soil temperature. celsius

attribute text: delta_13C  13C/12C ratio. The correction for isotopic fractionation (i.e., the isotopic composition of the sample), which is the parts per thousand difference (per mille) between the carbon 13 of the sample, and the content of the international PDB standard carbonate. If this was not calculated originally for the sample, values can be estimated based on material type (see Chapter 5 of the CALIB Manual at: http://calib.qub.ac.uk/calib/manual/chapter5.html). partsPerThousand
label: 'Soil heterotrophic respiration under manipulated conditions'
description: The respiration rate of heterotrophic organisms (animals and microbes) summed per unit area and time, occuring in soil, and during a experiment in which some condition has been manipulated or altered to understand its effect.

attribute text: Flag_delta_13C  QA/QC flags for 13C/12C ratio. The correction for isotopic fractionation (i.e., the isotopic composition of the sample), which is the parts per thousand difference (per mille) between the carbon 13 of the sample, and the content of the international PDB standard carbonate. If this was not calculated originally for the sample, values can be estimated based on material type (see Chapter 5 of the CALIB Manual at: http://calib.qub.ac.uk/calib/manual/chapter5.html). (flagging criteria, where "x" is delta_13C: )

attribute text: NPP_wet NPP Wet The seasonal rate of M. pyrifera biomass production in units of wet mass (kg m-2 day-1). This variable is calculated by integrating the instantaneous rate of production during each period and dividing by the number of days (as described in Section I.B Equation 2). Production for all days in each season is averaged. kilogramPerMeterSquaredPerDay
label: Net Primary Production Carbon Flux
description: Gross primary production (GPP) minus autotrophic respiration (AR) per unit ground or water area and time.

attribute text: FSC_carbon FSC Carbon The carbon mass of the foliar standing crop of M. pyrifera (kg m-2, excluding sporophylls and holdfast). These data are obtained by first calculating the carbon mass of each plant, using methods detailed in Section I.B Measuring standing crop, and then dividing the total carbon mass of all plants in the plot by the area of the plot. Plants without at least one frond longer than 1m are excluded. kilogramPerMeterSquared
label: carbon mass

attribute text: FSC_nitrogen FSC Nitrogen The nitrogen mass of the foliar standing crop of M. pyrifera (kg m-2, excluding sporophylls and holdfast). These data are obtained by first calculating the nitrogen mass of each plant, using methods detailed in Section I.B Measuring standing crop, and then dividing the total nitrogen mass of all plants in the plot by the area of the plot. Plants without at least one frond longer than 1m are excluded. kilogramPerMeterSquared
label: nitrogen mass

attribute text: SE_FSC_wet SE FSC Wet The standard error in our estimate of foliar standing crop in units of wet mass (kg m-2). This estimate is produced using Monte Carlo methods, as described in Section I.B Quantifying Uncertainty. The error in wet mass includes two types of error. Observer error consists of errors made in the number of plants sampled and in the measurement of their size. Regression errors include variability in the allometric relationships used to calculate the size of the three plant sections, as well as uncertainty in the length:wet-mass conversion ratio kilogramPerMeterSquared
label: 'Soil heterotrophic respiration under manipulated conditions'
description: The respiration rate of heterotrophic organisms (animals and microbes) summed per unit area and time, occuring in soil, and during a experiment in which some condition has been manipulated or altered to understand its effect.

attribute text: SE_FSC_carbon SE FSC Carbon The standard error in our estimate of foliar standing crop in units of carbon mass (kg m-2). This estimate is produced using Monte Carlo methods, as described in Section I.B Quantifying Uncertainty. The error in carbon mass includes two types of error. Observer error consists of errors made in the number of plants sampled and in the measurement of their size. Regression errors include variability in the allometric relationships used to calculate the size of the three plant sections, as well as uncertainty in the length:wet-mass, wet-mass:dry-mass and dry-mass:carbon-mass conversion ratios. kilogramPerMeterSquared
label: carbon mass

attribute text: SE_FSC_nitrogen SE FSC Nitrogen The standard error in our estimate of foliar standing crop in units of nitrogen mass (kg m-2). Observer error consists of errors made in the number of plants sampled and in the measurement of their size. Regression errors include variability in the allometric relationships used to calculate the size of the three plant sections, as well as uncertainty in the length:wet-mass, wet-mass:dry-mass and dry-mass:nitrogen-mass conversion ratios. kilogramPerMeterSquared
label: nitrogen mass
